<div class="article-headline" id="Headline">GRANOLA-STUFFED BAKED APPLES</div>



<div class="article-in-image" id="image1"><img src="images/page042.article001.image1.jpg" class="article-in-image" alt=""/></div>
<div class="separator-line" id="separatorLine"> <div class="invisible">empty</div> </div>
<div class="articleImageCaption" id="ImageCaption">Sweet apple cider permeates the apples as t hey bake, which keeps sugar use to a minim um and calories in check.</div>
<div class="articleImageCredit" id="ImageCredit">PHOTOGRAPHY BY WILLIAM DICKEY</div>
<div class="article-body" id="Body"><p class="no-indent">Makes 8 servings </p><br/><p class="no-indent">4 firm baking apples (such as Braeburn) </p><p class="no-indent">2 cups granola* </p><p class="no-indent">½ cup chopped dried figs </p><p class="no-indent">¼ cup dark brown sugar </p><p class="no-indent">4 tablespoons butter, melted </p><p class="no-indent">½ teaspoon vanilla extract </p><p class="no-indent">1½ cups apple cider </p><br/><p class="no-indent">1. Preheat oven to 350º. Cut apples in half, cutting through stem and bottom ends. Carefully scoop out and discard apple pulp and core, leaving a ¼-inch shell. Place apples in a 13x9-inch baking dish. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">2. In a medium bowl, stir together granola, figs, sugar, butter, and vanilla. Spoon granola mixture into apple halves. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">3. Pour cider around apples, and cover with aluminum foil. Bake for 20 minutes. Remove foil and bake for 20 to 25 minutes longer or until apples are tender. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">*We used Bear Naked Peak Protein Granola.</p></div>
